<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from the Chartered Institution of Highways &amp; Transportation (LTD0037)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Chartered Institution of Highways &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transportation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(LTD0037)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT is a membership organisation representing over 12,500 people who work in the highways and transportation sector.  CIHT memb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers plan, design, build, operate and maintain best-in-class transport systems and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT welcomes the opportunity t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o submit evidence to the Committee’s call for evidence. CIHT responses are based on inputs from members of the CIHT who have experience from across the local government H&amp;T sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Investment in infrastructure to support UK economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">growth is essential and business investor confidence that can be placed in the delivery of that infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vital. Uncertainty in this regard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">place the UK at a competitive disadvantage in global markets.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clarity and certainty on the timi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng of infrastructure investment comes less from change in the decision making process itself, but from having a clear vision of the strategic priorities for the UK.  The identification of those strategic infrastructure priorities has to be driven by an und</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">erstanding of the key spatial priorities for the UK economy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-10.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Progress with the preparation of the National Policy Statement on National Networks is therefore welcomed by the CIHT, providing the potential opportunity to set out a clear long-term framew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ork for the development of the country’s transport infrastructure.  However, it is essential that such a policy statement sits within a broader spatial strategy for the country, including, housing, jobs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and infrastructure. One that takes accou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt of, and builds upon, the economic strengths and potential of key sub-national areas.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  CIHT will be responding to the government’s consultation in due course.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-10.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Such a framework at the national level would provide a clear strategic framework within which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> detailed proposals could be developed by partners at the local level: for the purposes of this submission the argument assumes that the most appropriate ‘local level’ is the functional economic area.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-3.8pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Such considerations become all the more pertinent with the establishment of the Local Growth Fund.  Lord Heseltine’s report ‘No Stone Unturned’ identified the critical importance for the UK to target investment in infrastructure to support economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the need to prioritise that investment if the UK economy is to be globally competitive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-10.9pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local decision making on transport expenditure?  What are the advantages and disadvantag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">es of the Government’s approach?  Are there better models?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government’s proposals to devolve decision making on expenditure ultimately fits in with their localism agenda – devolving power and responsibility from a national to local level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The over-ri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ding consideration for any decision making process is the need to ensure the timely and efficient delivery of the outcomes being sought.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The timescales associated with the identification, development and subsequent implementation of major transport scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s are lengthy: a factor that needs to be taken into account whenever reviewing the need for change to the decision making process for prioritising and allocating funding.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Within the last five years the decision making process for allocating funds to inves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t in transport infrastructure has undergone repeated and fundamental change – from the prioritisation of schemes on a regional/sub national basis, to centralised decision making, to devolution to Local Transport Boards and now to non-statutory partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> led by the Local Enterprise Partnerships working in partnership with local authorities and other partners.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Change to the decision making process is in itself not inherently a bad thing.  However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">it needs to be remembered that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> any change temporarily adds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inertia to the delivery process.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation (CIHT) is of the view that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">profession’s collective ability to improve the efficiency and speed of delivery of infrastructure is inextricably linked to the extent to which there is a degree of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">continuity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> and certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">basis of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decision making process.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The creation of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Single Local Growth Fund should assist with certainty of the funding stream.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Devolution of decision making to the local level has been accompanied by a simplified approach to planning policy.  Whilst the introduction of the National Planning Policy Framew</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ork has simplified the overarching policy framework, there remains an expectation within the profession, as to the need to retain and reference technical guidance and/or advice.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The establishment of Local Enterprise Partnerships</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LEPs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, followed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the opportunity for local partners to work on the development of City-Deal proposals, and now the prospect of Growth Deals, have led to the development of stronger working relationships between public sector organisations, the business community and academ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ia.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  There remains a need to ensure the same level of duty to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cooperate (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consider neighbouring authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> applies to LEPs and Planning Authorities as the Traffic Management Act places on Local Highway Authorities to address cross boundary concerns</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such initiatives </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> encourage the development of a single narrative for a functional economic area – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enabl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local partners to better articulate the inter-relationship between investment in transport infrastructure, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">environment, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing and skills in support of economic growth across their area.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst agreeing with the government’s move towards devolution, there is a danger that local response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could be very local and not joined up, leading to inconsistencies.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local partners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be allowed to build upon this by continuing to be allowed to develop bespoke governance and working arrangements for their area that best reflect their local circumstances.  However, it is accepted that the governance and working arrangements should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be subject to the approval of Government: to ensure that devolution of funding (with the potential for being held accountable to Parliament) is vested in an appropriately constituted set up.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterpri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">se partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes?  What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is difficul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t to make a complete assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the new arrangements as not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enough time has yet passed to make a proper evaluation. Some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are also further ahead and working more effectively than others.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIHT argues that a discussion on the governance and working arrangements at the local level should differentiate between the forum in which decisions on investment priorities are made and the arrangements in place to deliver that investment on the grou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The previous attempt to devolve decision making on the allocation of investment in major transport schemes – through the process of Regiona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l Funding Allocations – enabled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decision makers to use their knowledge to prioritise the available trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">port funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">co-ordinate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that investment with the funds available for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">housing and economic development.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT argues that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">importance of adopting a co-ordinated approach r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mains as valid today as it did then – travel is a derived demand.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ey issue that needs consideration as part of this Inquiry is that of the av</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ilability of the technical and political skills required to enable the decision making process to operate efficiently.  Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authorities continue to be the main repository</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for these skills within the local area.  It is therefore unsurprising that many Local Enterprise Partnerships look to their Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authorities to provide the technical support on transport related matters.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIHT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> argues that the role of Local Highway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Integrated Transport Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in this regard should be acknowledged more explicitly across Government.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the absence of such acknowledgement, a consequence of the on-going financial pressures wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">thin the public sector is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">loss of existing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">skills</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This remove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> capacity and capability within the authorities at the very time when there is an increased need for the public sector to provide strong leadership in the development and delivery of major transport schemes.  An added threat to the skills base is the contr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">action in size and scope of local authority activities.  Change of this type reduces the opportunities and capacity of local authorities to train and develop the skills required to maintain the skills base in the longer term.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As is the case with many othe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r professions, that of transport planning faces the challenges of an aging demographic.  As a professional body the CIHT is actively supporting the development of appropriate skills within the existing workforce as well as encouraging future generations to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> enter the profession.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A ‘light touch’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spatial strategy, supported by a National Policy Statement on National Ne</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tworks, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would provide such co-ordinated approach at the national level.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e CIHT argues that this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would have two immediate benefits.  Firstly it would reinforce the need for increased cross-Departmental working within Whitehall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in the process supporting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the establishment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Local Growth Fund.  Secondly, it would provide local partners with a clear context within which to develop their local proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">: proposals that reflect local priorities and which are outcome focused.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issue of transport scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s that cross local authority boundaries has to be considered in the context of the issues that each scheme might raise.  Where a cross </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">boundary scheme is of national significance in its own right, or forms part of a wider corridor approach that is of natio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nal significance, it would seem appropriate for that to be reflected in the national framework.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key consideration for any potential scheme (not just ones that are cross boundary) must be an understanding of the outcome it delivers and how that relates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the agreed outcomes for the relevant functional economic area.   By focusing on the delivery of outcomes, schemes that cross local authority boundaries should not be disadvantaged.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with Gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">nment departments and national transport agencies?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n a recent workshop hosted by CIHT on behalf of the DfT and HA and including Local Authorities and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ps it became clear that there were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">good</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> working practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> between</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Local Authorities and the Highways Agency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important that this relationship is maintained and improved upon once the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Highways Agency becomes a GoCo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, ensuring that a duty to cooperate and the economic growth agenda are covered by any new holistic performance specification. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Improved certainty of funding for the newly formed Highways Agency should assist local areas better understand, inform and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">respond to the Agency’s plans.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It should also improve local networks to meet the wider economic growth agenda.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Agency should also have a better understanding on how it can and should involve local bodies.   Customers view the highway network as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a whole and local bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the HA and other stakeholders need to recognise this.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many authorities are taking some if not all of the standard methodologies developed by the Highways Maintenance Efficiency Programme </span><a href="http://www.highwaysefficiency.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">(HMEP),</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a sector led, DfT sponsored programme.  This is a positive trend and should be encouraged by all.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also important for the DfT to ensure that other government departments recognise the cross-cutting nature of transport and the cros</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s-sector benefits that can result from transport investment (e.g. health, climate change, education, air quality and access to key services).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the establishment of LEPs has led to stronger working relationships between public and private sectors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there remains further room for improved and more effective working. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It will be essential that there is coordination and cooperation between local bodies.  Whilst there are some very good examples </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of good local working practices, there is a danger of unev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en development and funding which could lead to inconsistencies. There can also be different skills levels and types between areas.  A higher skill level would be seen as a huge advantage to an areas ability to attract investors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Do the current funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities?  How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One aspect of private sector funding for transport that gives cause for concern is that secured throug</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h the planning system.  Whilst experience with the Community Infrastructure Levy is limited to date, there is a growing concern that the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secure an appropriate contribution towards transport infrastructure through the planning system is becom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing more difficult.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This concern is compounded by the fact that up to 25% of Community Infrastructure Levy monies secured will be directed in accordance with the priorities identified by neighbourhood communities.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is an inherent inflexibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">present within the Community Infrastructure Levy when compared with the previous S106 regime.  In the latter the need to secure an appropriate contribution towards transport infrastructure could be driven back into the land value if necessary.  That flexib</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ility is lost as a result of the introduction of the Community Infrastructure Levy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Failure to address the challenges associated with securing appropriate contributions for transport infrastructure through the planning system will inevitably increase the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pressure on other funding sources.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A move from grants to competitive bidding rounds for pots of funding could be a drain on already scare resources</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the Single Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Growth Fund have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Devolution of decision making on funding must be accompanied by extending the scope for local partners to determine the basis on which their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local priorities are arrived at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Variations in approach to reflect local circumstances should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e encouraged, confident in the fact that the national spatial strategy provides </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">appropriate strategic context.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The closer one can align policy making with responsibility for the allocation of funds, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater the opportunity to improve the efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and timeliness of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decision making process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is essential that the local governance and working arrangements associated with the devolution of decision making and funding reflect the views of the public sector organisations, the business community a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd academia.  It is particularly important that the views of one sector do not dominant.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is essential that the allocation of funds from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Single </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Growth Fund is not overly focused on investment in new infrastructure to unlock development oppor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tunities.  Public sector organisations, and in particular the Local Transport Authorities, will be keen to ensure that significant investment continues to be made in maintaining the existing transport infrastructure.  The CIHT has consistently argued the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ase for investment in maintenance of the existing asset as being of equal, if not greater, significance when it comes to supporting economic growth in the round.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a danger that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivery could be fragmented and lack overall cohesion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which coul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d lead to inefficiencies of scale.  As mentioned in 4.5 the use of HMEP, encouraging sharing of learning/best practices and set ways of operating will help to drive efficiencies into delivery at a local level.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etter forward visibility of public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector funding (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i.e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> five years plus) would enable local bodies to better develop a clear strategy and provisional programme and therefore lever private sector contributions and other joint funding to deliver a more secure programme of infrastructure schem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Flexibility of Strategic public sector funding to enable more contributions to schemes that are not on the strategic network but contribute to strategic objectives</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure?  What scope is there for the use of alternative funding schemes?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many Local Transport Authorities have established long-term contractual arrangements with private sector delivery partners who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support them in fulfilling their statutory duties.  Increasingly Local Transport Authorities are exploring with these partners the opportunity to develop more innovative approaches to financing the delivery of major transport schemes.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 25.1pt; text-indent:-25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The opportunity f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or local partners to leverage in additional funding (as opposed to financing delivery of schemes with funding already secured) is again something that Local Transport Authorities are exploring.  The covenant of local authorities in the UK remains very attr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">active to institutional investors.  Government support for innovative solutions led by Local Transport Authorities may enable additional funding to be leveraged more cost effectively than if led by the private sector.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">7.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such an approach could be seen as r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">einforcing the devolution of decision making and funding to local partnerships.  It could also be used to reinforce other Government initiatives designed to increase the extent to which funding raised locally is retained within the local economy.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">lear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The lines of accountability are unclear.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  CIHT believes that LTBs, LEPs should be democratically accountable and representative, it is essential that the develop</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment of local scheme priorities fits with existing statutory plans.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Elected members from district councils and, in the metropolitan areas, the Integrated Transport Authorities, should have a clear and prominent role in the process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.3pt; text-indent:-21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">8.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> our view, encouragement should be given for membership of the LTBs to be extended to other bodies, as relevant, including the Highways Agency, Network Rail, local Chambers of Commerce, key transport operators, and representative bodies in relation to publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ic transport </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The approach set out in this submission to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">establishing the local governance and working arrangements, if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supported </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">through the publication of a ‘light-touch’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national spatial strategy would provide clarity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the lines of accountability for local decision making on transport expenditure.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CIHT argues that clarity and stability in the decision making process is essential in order to provide certainty for scheme promoters to invest staff time and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">valuable revenue funding in the development of proposals.  It is also essential in order to provide confidence to business investors who are looking for a modern and efficient transport system to support economic growth.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Constant change to the decision ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">king process in recent years has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not given scheme promoters and their delivery partners the confidence to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">make the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">invest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ment in scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">development that would enable th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">long-term investment programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to come forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a consequence, w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hen opportunities to secure funding from Government have arisen so the likelihood </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increases that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some of that funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">allocated to opportunistic schemes simply because they are ready</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  The existence of an agreed programme of investment determined locall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y within the framework provided by a national spatial strategy would help ensure that the funds available are allocated to the most appropriate schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT submit that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">introduction of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Single </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Growth Fund affords the opportunity to devel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">op a truly devolved decision making and funding arrangement.  However, in order to ensure that such an approach is efficient and delivers timely investment it is important that Government provides a ‘light touch’ national spatial strategy: one that is supp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orted by appropriate national policy statements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">  </span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>